article.headline: Nets win 4 of last 5; Magic drop 12 in a row
article.linkText: Jefferson helps Nets pull away from Magic
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- With about three minutes left in the third quarter, Kenyon Martin gingerly put weight on his left knee and looked toward the New Jersey Nets' bench. He left the game a minute later amid concern his comeback was in jeopardy on the eve of the playoffs. Martin returned to the court early in the fourth quarter of the Nets' 101-81 win over the Orlando Magic on Thursday, but there are serious questions about the knee with the postseason a week away. "It was starting to hurt. I went out and iced it," said Martin, who was making his first start since March 18. "That calmed it down. I wanted to go back in and give it a try." Martin finished with 14 points and seven rebounds in 32 minutes in only his third game since being sidelined with tendinitis in his left knee. "Maybe the more I play, the less it will ache," Martin said. "I hope this is not going to be the story, but we'll have to wait and see. I'm not worried, just concerned that it's going to keep on like that." While Martin raised concerns about his knee, fellow All-Star Jason Kidd didn't make anyone worry in his first start since being sidelined with a bone bruise in his left knee on March 18. "Everything went well," Kidd said after scoring eight points and handing out seven assists in 31 minutes. "Sitting for a little bit and coming back in, I wanted to see if it would be stiff, but it felt good." Kidd and Martin were not sure whether they will play in Indiana on Friday night, the Nets first back-to-back games since they returned earlier this week. Kidd banked in a half-court heave at the end of the third quarter to give the Nets the lead for good. They sent the Magic to their 12th straight loss. After Kidd gave the Nets the lead, Richard Jefferson and Brian Scalabrine took over in helping the Nets win for the fourth time in five games. The setback assured Orlando at least a tie for the league's worst record. With one more loss in the final three regular-season games, the Magic (19-60) will be assured of having the best chance to win the draft lottery. Juwan Howard had 21 points and Drew Gooden added 20 points and 12 rebounds for Orlando, which has not won since March 10 and again did not have Tracy McGrady in the lineup. "It's been like this the whole season," Gooden said. "The whole season." Kidd's desperation shot was only his third basket on 10 attempts. He walked to the bench with a big grin after making it. "That's about my range right now," Kidd said. "I can't make anything too close. So I have to back up some." Jefferson took over in the fourth quarter, igniting a 17-8 run with a slam off Rodney Rogers' pass. Jefferson had all of his 11 fourth-quarter points in the run. He also had three assists, two setting up a layup and a slam by Scalabrine, who had 11 of his season-high 15 points in the quarter. Jefferson finished with 21 points.

Game notes
The game was played on the 10th anniversary of Orlando clinching its first playoff berth with a 117-103 win over Detroit. Someone named Shaquille O'Neal led the Magic with 40 points. ... Magic F-C Steven Hunter missed his second straight game with an eye infection. ... Rogers scored five points, and now is 16 shy of 9,000 for his career. ...The Magic had a franchise-record 19-game losing streak earlier this season.
